The body of former nominated MP Mark Too was flown to Nairobi yesterday and taken to the Lee Funeral Home where it will stay pending burial arrangements.A postmortem will be carried out to determine the cause of death.Too, 60, collapsed at his home on Saturday in the bathroom and workers broke the doors to find him unconscious on the floor. He was rushed to St Lukes Hospital in Eldoret, where he was pronounced dead on arrival.Kapseret MP Oscar Sudi and Too's widows Mary and Sofi were among leaders who escorted the body to Eldoret Airport where it was flown to the city.Nairobi Governor Evans Kidero described Too as a personal friend and a man with a unique spirit that penetrated ethnic, racial, religious and political boundaries. President Uhuru Kenyatta, Deputy President William Ruto, opposition leaders Raila Odinga, Musalia Mudavadi and Kalonzo Musyoka eulogised as a humorous, witty and friendly politician.His two widows Mary and Sofi Too along with his brother Clement Too held family meetings.Clement said the family would give details on then death this week as they prepare to bury Too.Hundreds of people yesterday thronged Too&rsquo;s homes in Eldoret town and at Kapseret near the Eldoret International Airport to console with the family. He also had another home at Kosirai, Nandi.Too was popularly known as Bwana Dawa or Mr Fix-It during the regime of retired President Daniel Moi because of the role he played to help Moi deal with intricate political situations.Dr Ahmed Faraj of St Luke's said Too had sought treatment at the hospital on Christmas Day complaining of stomach pains, but he declined to be admitted for a night at the facility. He had been in a jovial mood and had arrived in Eldoret from Nairobi and Nakuru.Too was born in Ndebunet, Nandi county, and attended Ndebunet Primary School.He served as an assistant minister in retired President Moi's government, but was forced to resign in 2001 to pave way for President Uhuru Kenyatta.Too once served as chairman of the then East African Standard newspaper and unsuccessfully ran for Eldoret South MP.He was a close aide of Moi, acting as an ambassador at large and forging international political and economic links.Too played a role in peace missions in Congo, Uganda, Sudan and Angola.He was also a prominent farmer and a close ally of top politicians in the Rift Valley.Too also served as chairman of Lonrho East Africa. His last public function was on December 12 during the Jamhuri Day celebrations at the 64 Stadium in Eldoret.Uasin Gishu Governor Jackson Mandago said he had also lost a close family friend and a friend of the county government.&ldquo;He was very committed to supporting the county and we will miss his contribution to development in the region,&rdquo; he said.Mandago visited the family to condole with them.